snippet.textDisplay:
7:31 Fast food employee here. It is hard to understand costumers through the speaker and headset. The person taking your order is more than likely the same person taking the money for drive thru orders, so they're multitasking (taking your order as well as money and/or listening to other customers at window). The person in drive thru also has more tasks than just standing around taking orders. Also, if there's other people with headsets and they use the headsets for communication, it's hard to hear customers' orders. A lot of people order differently, so it can be very confusing to understand exactly what a customer wants. (Especially, when you've asked a simple "yes" or "no" question and they completely ignore it by repeating their whole order or just saying the exact same thing over. It doesn't help. Stop.)
It may seem dumb, but we say "Yeah, but we didn't charge you." because several customers expect us to just give them free food. We cannot. And a lot of the time, customers just tell us to forget about the items left off the order because they're irritated. It's also said out of defense because the person handing the food out didn' put your order in, so it is not their fault. I highly recommend reviewing your order on the screen and checking the receipt as soon as you've paid! And please, remember what you've actually ordered. Employees can also read your order back (we're trained to, but it's so time consuming and most customers don't listen, so we don't bother).
Thanks for coming to my TED talk.
